entury. Drawing extensively on archival and musical materials, Aaron Copland and the American Legacy of Gustav Mahler offers the first detailed exploration of Copland's multifaceted relationshipwith Mahler's music and its lasting consequences for music in America. Matthew Mugmon demonstrates that Copland, inspired by Mahler's example, blended modernism and romanticism in shaping a vision for American music in the twentieth century, and that he did so through his multiple roles as composer, teacher, critic, and orchestral tastemaker. Copland's career-long engagement with Mahler's music, as Mugmon compellingly illustrates, intersected with Copland's own Jewish identity and with his links to such towering figures in American music as Nadia Boulanger, Serge Koussevitzky, and Leonard Bernstein. MATTHEW MUGMON is Assistant Professor of Music at the University of Arizona.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMusicxHistory and criticismy20th centuryzUnited States. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAaron Copland.  aAmerican music.  aGustav Mahler.  acomposer.  amusic influence.  atwentieth century.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311143102440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787445635?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787445635423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787445635/original  a978-3-11-143102-4  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles